article.headline: Iowa 83, Minnesota 68
article.story: MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Iowa coach Steve Alford appreciated his team's resilience, coming off an embarrassing defeat at home. Minnesota coach Dan Monson will be anxiously waiting to see the same thing. Jeff Horner set the tone with a pair of 3-pointers in the game's first 1{ minutes, finishing with a career-high 23 points for the Hawkeyes in an 83-68 victory over the Gophers on Tuesday night. Four other players had double-digit points for Iowa (9-4, 2-1 Big Ten), including Brody Boyd with 15. "I just appreciate ... getting off the mat the way they did after such a disappointing loss," said Alford, who was angered by a lack of veteran leadership following a 77-68 defeat to Northwestern on Saturday in Iowa City. Kris Humphries had 17 points for the Gophers (8-6, 0-2), who will have a difficult time even making the NIT this year if they can't start playing better defense. Adam Boone scored 13 points for Minnesota, which is second-to-last in the conference in points allowed -- an average of more than 75 per game. "I really don't feel like we lost because we didn't score," Humphries said. "I think we lost because they worked harder than we did." With Sean Sonderleiter starting at center for Jared Reiner, the Hawkeyes' four seniors -- Sonderleiter, Reiner, Boyd and Glen Worley -- made sizable contributions. Sonderleiter had 12 points and went 8-for-9 from the free-throw line, Reiner had 11 points and eight rebounds in 17 minutes and Worley added 11 points. "The key tonight was all four of them had productivity," Alford said. "That's what we've got to have." The Hawkeyes, who won their first six games but haven't had consecutive victories since, raised expectations by beating No. 8 Louisville and Purdue. But they've frustrated Alford with their inconsistency. "We can do this every game, the seniors, no matter what the underclassmen do," Boyd said. "It really revolves around us." Humphries, a freshman who leads the Big Ten in both scoring and rebounding, had the Williams Arena crowd of 13,032 roaring after a wide-open dunk cut the Iowa lead to 36-33 early in the second half. The Hawkeyes, however, went on a 10-0 run after that to pull away, and the spurt included this telling sequence: --A misguided pass bounced off Michael Bauer's shin and out of bounds for a Minnesota turnover. --Gophers point guard Boone got a steal but missed a fast-break layup on the other end. --Worley sank a wide-open 3-pointer from the top of the key for Iowa to extend the lead to 44-33. "All we can do is keep working to get better," Monson said. "We're not very good right now. It's not our defense. It's not our offense. It's the way we're playing at both ends of the court. "It was a combination of too many things we've got to fix." The Gophers play at Ohio State on Saturday and at Purdue next Wednesday. "If we want to save our season ... we have to start playing well," Boone said. The second half was very physical and out-of-control at times, and Minnesota came within 10 -- at 72-62 -- on a 3-pointer by Humphries with 2:18 left. But the Hawkeyes held off the late charge, sealing the victory at the foul line. The Big Ten's second-worst free-throw shooting team missed nine of them but made 32 -- earning 27 more foul shots than the Gophers, a rarity on the road and a big reason why the Hawkeyes won. "I always stress free throws, because that's who I was as a player," said Alford, a star at Indiana under coach Bob Knight in the 1980s. "I think we're a plus-140 on the year. Those are huge numbers, if we just make them." Iowa entered the game having held opponents to a field-goal percentage of 38.8, and Minnesota shot only 41.3 percent -- 34.4 percent before halftime. The Hawkeyes befuddled the Gophers with their zone defense, an uncharacteristic concept for a Knight- or Alford-coached team. "I'm sure I'll get a call from Coach Knight after this one," Alford joked.
